Data Gathering¶

In cells below, we would gather all three pieces of data for this project and load them in the notebook.

1) Extracting enhanced twitter archive provided¶

In [2]:
twitter_archive_df = pd.read_csv("twitter-archive-enhanced.csv")

2) Using Requests library to download the tweet image prediction (image_predictions.tsv)¶

In [3]:
url = 'https://d17h27t6h515a5.cloudfront.net/topher/2017/August/599fd2ad_image-predictions/image-predictions.tsv'
res = requests.get(url)
filename = url.split('/')[-1]
if not os.path.exists(filename):    
    with open(filename,"wb") as file:
        file.write(res.content)
        
# reading file image_predictions.tsv 

img_pred_df = pd.read_csv("image-predictions.tsv", sep='\t')

3) Extracting tweets from (tweet_json.txt)¶

In [4]:
tweets = []
tweet_file= 'tweet_json.txt'
with open(tweet_file,encoding='utf-8') as file:
    for lines in file:
        tweet_data = json.loads(lines)
        tweet_id = tweet_data['id']
        retweet_count = tweet_data['retweet_count']
        favorite_count = tweet_data['favorite_count']
        source = tweet_data['source']
        tweets.append({'tweet_id':tweet_id,'retweets_count':retweet_count,'favorite_count':favorite_count,'source':source})
    
tweets_df = pd.DataFrame(tweets)

Quality issues¶

twitter_archive¶

1. (+0000) to be removed at timestamp values.
2. Timestamp should be Datetime dtype. 
3. The source should be extracted from the hyperlink at source columns.
4. keeping only original tweets and no retweets.
5. Columns with NaN entries to be dropped.
6. Names as lower case and not valid names ('a','such','the','just','getting'). 
7. Presence of 0 and outliers values rating_numerator column.

Image_predictions dataframe.¶

8. Dropping rows in df_image_predictions with p1_dog == false.

Tidiness issues¶

  1. concatenate dog stages columns i.e. (doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo), there are cases with multiple dog stages in a row.
  2. df_tweets and df_image_predictions (jpg_url, p1, p1_conf) can be merged to df_twitter_archive as one datasets

Tidiness Issue #1:¶

Define: Concatenate dog stages columns i.e. (doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo), there are cases with multiple dog stages in a row.¶

Code¶

In [45]:
# Extracting desired column

DogStage = twitter_archive_clean[['tweet_id','name', 'doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo']]

df_dogstage = (DogStage.set_index(['tweet_id','name'])
         .replace('None', np.nan)
         .apply(lambda x: ','.join(x.dropna()), axis=1)
         .reset_index(name='dog_stage'))

# Merging to original dataframe

twitter_archive_clean = twitter_archive_clean.merge(df_dogstage, on=['tweet_id','name'], how='inner')

# dropping columns

twitter_archive_clean.drop(columns=['doggo','floofer','pupper','puppo'],inplace=True)

Insights #4: Is there a relationship between retweet_count and favorite_count?¶

In [63]:
sns.set_theme(color_codes=True)
plt.figure(figsize=(14,8))
sns.regplot(x = "retweets_count", y = "favorite_count", 
            data = data, color='red');
plt.title("A Graph of relationship between favorite count and retweet count",fontsize=20);
plt.xlabel("Retweets count",fontsize=18);
plt.ylabel("Favorite count", fontsize=18);

It can be observed from the above graph there exist a positive relationship between favorite count and retweets count. This implies dog with higher retweets are the most favorites. Let's further drive our points with testing the strenght of relationships.

In [64]:
np.corrcoef(data.retweets_count, data.favorite_count)
Out[64]:
array([[1.        , 0.91103578],
       [0.91103578, 1.        ]])

The above correlation coefficient output shows the strenght of relationship at 91%, which marks a very strong positive relationship between retweet counts and favorite counts.

It is observed in the dog stage; doggo with a prediction of Labrador_retriever has the highest retweets count with 795,151 retweets, but not necessarily the most favorite, as there exists puppo with the prediction of lakeland_terrier with a more favorite count of 132,810 than Labrador_retriever with the favorite count of 131,075. Although there exists a 91% relationship between retweets and favorites, the highest favorite still doesn't automatically define the most favorite in the Twitter archive under investigation.
